        "bl_text_GkFPXw": {
          "type": "bl_text",
          "settings": {
            "col_dk": "12",
            "col_tb": "12",
            "text_size": "40,15",
            "txt_align": "start",
            "sub_heading": "",
            "heading": "",
            "text": "<h3><br/>1. Vijay Sethupathi – Saree Realness in 'Super Deluxe.'</h3><p>This wasn’t a fashion statement — it was <strong>art</strong>.</p><p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vijay_Sethupathi\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Vijay Sethupathi </span></a>played a trans woman in <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Deluxe_(film)\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\"><em>Super Deluxe</em></span></a> with so much grace and grit that the saree wasn’t a costume — it was a character. His portrayal was layered, respectful, and way more nuanced than half the industry’s woke PR stunts.</p><p><strong>Power Moment: </strong>And guess what? He looked absolutely majestic in those traditional Madisar drapes.</p><p></p><h3>2. Allu Arjun – The Saree Step in ‘Pushpa 2.’</h3><p><a href=\"https://www.netflix.com/de/title/82006666\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Pushpa</span></a> wore a saree, <em>and the audience collectively lost their minds.</em></p><p>It was fierce. It was symbolic. It was unbothered. The look broke masculinity, femininity, and possibly the box office in one swift, silken motion.</p><p><strong>Power Moment:</strong><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allu_Arjun\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Allu Arjun</span></a> doesn’t wear sarees to be edgy. He does it because he <strong>can</strong>. And he looks like he’ll slap you with a sandal if you say otherwise.<br/><br/></p>",
            "subhd_color": "#222222",
            "hd_color": "#222222",
            "des_color": "#878787",
            "use_shadow": false,
