        "template--16761530319081__e7b55938-3dde-44ab-9365-66967e09d447-16829720379ce15b30-1": {
          "type": "bl_text",
          "settings": {
            "col_dk": "12",
            "col_tb": "12",
            "text_size": "40,15",
            "txt_align": "start",
            "sub_heading": "",
            "heading": "",
            "text": "<h3><br/>3. Riteish Deshmukh in Apna Sapna Money Money</h3><p>When <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/riteishd/\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Riteish</span></a> showed up in a saree, long wig, and heels, he wasn’t just cross-dressing — he was <em>acting</em>. In the film, he disguises himself as a woman to pull off a con, and what made it iconic was how comfortable he looked in the disguise. He didn’t mock the saree — he rocked it.</p><p><strong>Power moment:</strong> His comic timing, paired with graceful saree draping, gave “double role” a whole new meaning.</p><p></p><h3>4. Kamal Haasan as Lakshmi in Chachi 420</h3><p>This is <em>the</em> blueprint. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamal_Haasan\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Kamal Haasan</span></a> transformed into <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chachi_420\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Lakshmi Godbole</span></a> — a stern but lovable nanny — and wore a saree for nearly the entire film. His look wasn’t played for cheap laughs. Instead, he brought dignity, warmth, and even elegance to the role.</p><p><strong>Power moment:</strong> Watching Kamal Haasan fold a saree, manage a pallu, and perform high drama — all without breaking character — is a masterclass.</p>",
            "subhd_color": "#222222",
            "hd_color": "#222222",
