        "bl_text_Fk8iaH": {
          "type": "bl_text",
          "settings": {
            "col_dk": "12",
            "col_tb": "12",
            "text_size": "40,15",
            "txt_align": "start",
            "sub_heading": "",
            "heading": "",
            "text": "<h3><br/>5. Govinda as that incredible lover in Aunty No. 1</h3><p>You can’t talk about men in sarees and not mention Govinda. In this outrageous comedy, he plays a man posing as an older woman — “Aunty” — to help his friends impress women. The result? Loud makeup, dramatic drapes, and unbeatable dance moves.</p><p><strong>Power moment:</strong> <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Govinda_(actor)\"><span style=\"text-decoration:underline\">Govinda</span></a> giving full sass and swagger in a saree, commanding attention in every frame.</p><h2>Why This Matters</h2><p>Sure, some of these performances leaned into comedy. But beneath the humor lies something more important: <strong>a quiet breakdown of gendered clothing norms</strong>. These actors wore sarees on screen — and didn’t flinch. Some looked fabulous. Some made us laugh. But all of them reminded us that fabric has no gender.</p><p>And if they can wear it with confidence, why can’t we?</p><h2>Final Thought</h2><p><em>It’s time we stop laughing at men in sarees and start applauding the ones who wear it with dignity, boldness, and joy.</em></p><p>Because the saree doesn’t care about your gender — it only cares how you carry it.</p>",
            "subhd_color": "#222222",
            "hd_color": "#222222",
            "des_color": "#878787",
